Kube-API Server - The Brain of Kubernetes

Kube-API Server is the main entry point for all requests in a Kubernetes cluster. It handles communication between users, applications, and cluster components. It validates requests, applies security rules, and updates cluster state.

1. Authentication - Who Are You?

When you send a request like kubectl get pods, Kubernetes first checks who you are. This is authentication.
Authentication means prove your identity.

How Kubernetes Authenticates

Method	               Used By
TLS Certificates    	Kubelet, controllers, nodes
Service Accounts    	Pods and services inside Kubernetes
Bearer Tokens	        External tools like Helm
OIDC (OpenID Connect)	Google, Azure, etc. login
Webhook Token	        Custom authentication using APIs

Example

If you try to kubectl delete pod, API Server checks if your token is valid.

Valid → Request goes to authorization
Invalid → Request is denied

Real Benefit
Only verified people and services can access the cluster. No fake entries.

2. Authorization - What Can You Do?

Once Kubernetes knows who you are, it checks what actions you can perform.
Authorization means checking permissions.

How Kubernetes Handles Authorization

Method	            Description
RBAC	            Most common. Uses roles and bindings
ABAC	            Uses JSON policy files
Webhook	            Custom authorization via APIs
Node Authorization	For kubelets to access only their own resources

Example
If you are a developer, you may only get pods but not delete them. If you try to delete without permission, request is denied.

Real Benefit
Different people get different access levels. Junior team cannot break production.

3. Admission Control - Extra Security Checks

After authentication and authorization, admission controllers check the request before applying it to the cluster.
Think of it like airport security checking your luggage before boarding.

What Admission Controllers Do

Action	            Description
Validate Requests	Ensure they follow cluster policies
Modify Requests	    Auto add labels, annotations, or defaults
Enforce Security	Block risky actions like root containers

Common Admission Controllers

Controller	                What It Does
PodSecurityPolicy       	Blocks privileged containers
ResourceQuota	            Enforces CPU and memory limits
MutatingAdmissionWebhook	Auto adds missing labels or fields
ValidatingAdmissionWebhook	Validates requests before applying

Example

If you create a pod that uses too much memory, ResourceQuota rejects it.
If you create a pod without labels, MutatingAdmissionWebhook adds them automatically.

Real Benefit
Security and resource limits are enforced automatically. No one can bypass cluster rules.

4. Watch for Updates - Real Time Tracking

API Server watches the entire cluster and notifies clients of changes in real time.
Think of it like a group where everyone gets instant updates.

How Watch Works

Clients like kubectl and monitoring tools subscribe to updates
API Server pushes updates whenever resources change (new pods, deleted nodes)
This prevents clients from constantly asking API Server, saving resources

Example

If a pod is deleted, all watching clients get instant notification
kubectl get pods --watch shows real time updates without running the command repeatedly

Real Benefit
No constant polling. Cluster events reach controllers instantly. Less network and CPU waste.